There is a wealth of infection-related data produced every day. 

We should be value-adding to the cost of obtaining it by ensuring it is available to all.
#MoreCommunication

•Why aren't such data comprehensively presented, simple to find &easy to interpret? 

I have no doubt we'd have had wider community understanding of aspects of this pandemic if such data had been easy to find for the media to ask questions & write explainers about, years ago

These are taxpayer-funded community client-sourced (our samples) testing outcomes.

•Why isn't there an expectation that they are also clearly communicated and retrospectively viewable by the public? Giving them some control can help them protect & educate themselves

•Is it okay to rely on volatile media websites for dashboards of limited real-time info? 
•Satisfactory to rely on international websites to find out the phylogenomics of monkeypox (etc) cases detected in Aus? Or media stories as our source to find out about this or that case?

Compare for SC2. The UK produces a range of flavours of info that we simply can't find in the open in Australia.
https://t.co/Ojkib7jeCx

•Why is it so hard to find genomics results? Using Flu/MPX/SARS-CoV-2 variants as examples. How has Omicron BA.2.12.1 travelled over the last few months? BA.4? XM? Which citizen scientist should I watch? Oh, they're taking a break. How much sequencing are we doing? From where?

Maybe a CDC will fix this communication failure and help standardise content and its provision. But nothing is stopping it from having been fixed long ago. And NSW shows that.

•Why don't we have detailed, easily accessible, stored retrospective data on all infections over time?

And I say this with the caveat that @NSWHealth is the gold standard in this area and does so much good work in these spaces. 

So we know it *can* be funded, the expertise exists and it just is possible.

Does Australia have a public health infection-related data-hoarding, education and communication problem? 

•Why is Australia so stingy with its data?
•Why are we so bad at community communication about preventing infections? 
•What is it about us?
